Data analysis

Table

Text

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The model’s total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.62) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.04. The model’s intercept, corresponding to group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 17.84 (S.E. = 0.50, p < .001, 95% CI [16.86, 18.83]). Within this model:

  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.13, S.E. = 0.71, p = 0.858, 95% CI [-1.26, 1.51]; Std. beta = 0.03, 95% CI [-0.32, 0.38])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.44, S.E. = 0.50, p = 0.384, 95% CI [-1.42, 0.55]; Std. beta = -0.11, 95% CI [-0.36, 0.14])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 2.17, S.E. = 0.73, p = 0.003, 95% CI [0.74, 3.60]; Std. beta = 0.55, 95% CI [0.19, 0.91])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
